===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|p}} – pictographic representation of a fire. Written as [[灬]] when at the bottom of a character, but still seen in the original form in the character [[灸]].

See also the top component of [[叟]] in its original form and the bottom part of [[赤]].

===Etymology===
{{etymon|zh|id=fire|:inh|sit-pro:*məj<id:fire><unc:1>}}
Possibly from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*məj}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler 2007}}; STEDT). However, see there for phonological problems.

{{zh-ref|Sagart and Baxter (2024)}} update their Old Chinese reconstruction to {{och-l|火|tr= {{IPAfont|*X.pˤərʔ}}}} (whence {{w|Middle Chinese|MC}} ''xwaX'' → ''huǒ'') and propose alternative cognacy to {{och-l|燹|tr= {{IPAfont|*X.pər(ʔ)-s}}}} (whence MC ''xwijH''), both being prefixed by unknown element {{IPAfont|X-}} which turned the labial plosive {{IPAfont|*p(ʰ)-}} into the fricative {{IPAfont|*xw-}}; moreover, both are cognates to {{och-l|燹|tr= {{IPAfont|*sə-pˤər(ʔ)-s}}}} (whence MC ''senX'' → ''xiǎn''). They also propose that aforesaid Chinese words are cognates to {{cog|tbq-pro|*par}} (i.e. STEDT Etymon #2152 {{m|tbq-pro|*bʷar ~ *pʷar||fire; burn; kindle; roast}}, see [https://stedt.berkeley.edu/~stedt-cgi/rootcanal.pl/etymon/2152 there] for descendants) as well as {{cog|map-pro|*dapuʀ||cooking fire, hearth}}.

